label chapter7:

    # [Scene: Old Estuary Boardwalk | Dawn]

    scene bg ch6_f99e88_1 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Warm, ascending strings with light percussive taps]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Distant hammers settling into silence, gulls arguing, the steady lap of tide against new reef modules]
    "You came here because you chose to stand with the barrio. You remember the decision like a bruise that softened into muscle — elbowing through municipal red tape, hauling salvaged oyster cages and woven willow, bargaining"
    "off a rusted barge for a day — each small victory braided into the wall beneath your feet. The work is visible now: kelp-rooted mattresses, interlaced mangrove plugs, reclaimed pallets sunk and anchored; it breathes and"
    "holds."
    "Your boots jar against the boardwalk. Salt and wet timber rise in a smell you have learned to read like weather. You can still feel the grit under your nails from yesterday; your jacket has a"
    "smear of clay where you dug, and the single glass-bead braid at your temple ticks against your collarbone as you turn to the crowd that gathered to see the breach closed."
    "Sofia stands at the rail, fingers worrying a ribbon of twine, eyes bright and wet. Teo is sprawled on the steps, elbow into his knees, grin smeared with grease and paint. Behind them, neighbors cluster —"
    "some in borrowed work vests, some in festival scarves — their faces lit by the same relieved, stubborn light you carry."
    show sofia_navarro at left:
        zoom 0.7

    sofia_navarro "Asha. Look at it. You did this."
    "You don't answer immediately. Instead you let the sound of the sea and the low murmur circulate through you. It's a collective breath you helped to teach the neighborhood to take. When you speak it is steady, practical but soft."
    show asha_rivera at right:
        zoom 0.7

    asha_rivera "We did it, Sofia. Everyone did."
    "Sofia reaches and squeezes your hand like an offering and a demand at once. There is gratitude, yes, but also the daily ledger of losses that still sits in her eyes. You can feel the weight"
    "of that and choose your words with the careful, patient mediations you've practiced for years."
    show mateo_teo_rivera at center:
        zoom 0.7

    mateo_teo_rivera "Mayor's on her way with the permits. She promised. It's—' (he waves a hand, searching) '—it's weird to think paper can be a shield, but Lila's got it. And the council clerk said the emergency clause flew through the first read."

    asha_rivera "Good. We'll keep a watch schedule, teach people how to maintain the planting sections, and Jun's team will run the sensor array."
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: A soft motor, the municipal vehicle pulling up; polite footsteps on wet wood]
    hide sofia_navarro
    hide asha_rivera
    hide mateo_teo_rivera

    scene bg ch6_f99e88_2 at full_bg
    show mayor_lila_ortega at left:
        zoom 0.7

    mayor_lila_ortega "Asha.' Her voice is small in the open air, but there's a solidity underneath — the city's weight learning how to be kinder. 'This is what I wanted to see. The council signed the emergency permit just now. We attached maintenance clauses and a labor credit for the cooperative."
    "You watch her face for the small skittishness that shows during negotiations; it is there for a heartbeat and then gone, replaced by something like satisfaction."
    show asha_rivera at right:
        zoom 0.7

    asha_rivera "You actually read the margin notes."
    "Mayor Lila: (half a laugh) 'I read them. And I called Leon three times to make sure the escrow language couldn't be gamed.' She studies the seawall like a curator, then meets your eyes. 'You were"
    "right to push for community control. The city can't afford to lose these neighborhoods. Not anymore.'"
    "The conversation threads outward — logistics, funding, the small legal teeth that will keep Aegis from walking away. Each subject is a new stitch in a shared garment. People speak, argue, laugh, and steadier hands pass"
    "out bowls of strong coffee and bowls of caldo that steam in the cool air. The relief is not a static thing; it moves through the crowd in practical measures: who's on damage patrol this week,"
    "which block needs extra sandbags in the next swell, who will teach the children how to plant the plugs come autumn."
    "Elias Hart arrives last, climbing down from the boardwalk with mud on his cuffs and a banner rolled in his hands — the same patchwork banner you'd argued over months ago. He pauses when he sees"
    "you. For a second the city and its noise narrow to his face: sun-bright hair damp at the temples, eyes the clear green you have always trusted for being blunt and true."
    show elias_hart at center:
        zoom 0.7

    elias_hart "Didn't expect to find the mayor here of all people."

    asha_rivera "Neither did I. But look at this.' You sweep your arm toward the seawall. 'We didn't let them design us out of our home."
    "Elias Hart's mouth quirks. He hasn't entirely softened the ways you sometimes clash — his impatience, your compromises — but there is warmth, threaded with the pride of someone who was there in the first line of work parties: hauling, laughing, being stubbornly present."

    elias_hart "You held everyone together in that room. It mattered."
    "(you let the praise land and then redirect)"

    asha_rivera "It was your banners and those midnight supply runs that kept people showing up, Elias. I couldn't have done the outreach alone."
    "He opens his mouth, then shuts it, then lets out a breath."

    elias_hart "We did it together. That—' (he lifts his hands) '—that's the thing I missed — being in the mess with people who are not afraid to get muddy."
    "The conversation between you and Elias spreads into another kind of rhythm: teasing, honest, punctuated by the practicalities you both love. Teo pipes in with a joke about the seawall's nickname; Sofia offers you a piece"
    "of sweet bread, warm and perfumed with citrus. Lila promises to fast-track training for maintenance crews. The city gives something that feels like a contract and the barrio gives back the labor and the trust."

    menu:
        "Accept Sofia's slice and eat by the rail":
            "You bite into the warm bread; it tastes like the market at first light — sun and sugar and salt. You let the comfort settle into your shoulders, grounding the victory in a small, domestic joy."
        "Decline and walk the length of the wall instead":
            "You want to feel every inch. You walk the wall, fingers skimming the woven reeds; you catalog the places that still need work and let the tally line the edges of your satisfaction."

    # --- merge ---
    "Both choices leave you connected to the work and the people, each producing a small, grounding moment before the day continues."
    # [Scene: Completed Living Seawall | Late Afternoon]
    hide mayor_lila_ortega
    hide asha_rivera
    hide elias_hart

    scene bg ch6_f99e88_3 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: A gentle swell of chorus and light percussion, hopeful but intimate]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Tide whispering, children's laughter carried like a buoyant thread]
    "Later, after permits are signed and the market hums toward evening, you take Elias with you to the outer parapet. The crowd thins. The city noise stays at the periphery like a distant tide; the two"
    "of you move into a small private shore where the work you finished can be touched and read like a book's last page."
    show asha_rivera at left:
        zoom 0.7

    asha_rivera "Walk with me."
    "He does. Barely a hand's length between you, there is space — the kind that used to yawn into arguments — now filled with small reconciliations. The light slants, gilding the braided beads in your hair"
    "and the lines at his eyes. You catalog what you love in the silence: the resilience scored into the wall, the smell of brine and soil, the way the rope rail hums under your fingers."
    show elias_hart at right:
        zoom 0.7

    elias_hart "You sounded different in that meeting. Less like you were compromising yourself and more like... like you were holding something for everyone."

    asha_rivera "Because I am. And because I finally stopped pretending that stubbornness alone would keep us safe.' (You look at him.) 'I borrowed stubbornness with patience this time."
    "He laughs, small and unrepentant."

    elias_hart "Patience? From you? That's a new species."

    asha_rivera "It wasn't easy."
    "He studies you like someone memorizes a map. His voice drops; the breeze pulls at a loose strand of his hair."

    elias_hart "I was stubborn too. I thought we could push harder and faster, but I forgot sometimes that the ground has to be ready or everything collapses. I didn't listen enough to the ways your plans keep people whole."

    asha_rivera "And I forgot that sometimes you need the shove. I was afraid of losing our community by bargaining with the city. I thought letting people bring in tech would mean they sell us out."

    elias_hart "Maybe it almost did. But look at this.' (He gestures to the braided oysters, the seedlings now rooting) 'We found a way that wasn't just one or the other."
    "There is a pause — the weight of what remains unsaid. For a time you both only listen: to the tide, to the remnant clinks of tools, to the far-off call of a market singer tuning up."

    elias_hart "Do you forgive me for the nights I dragged people into things without telling you? For the banners I painted without asking where you'd stand?"
    "(a slow inhale)"

    asha_rivera "I forgive you. For the nights I refused to march because I was afraid we'd lose control, forgive me for that too."
    "He reaches and folds his fingers with yours, no fanfare, no scripted line. The touch is quiet but binding."

    elias_hart "So what's next?"

    asha_rivera "We teach. We maintain. We keep the wall alive as a community practice, not a monument. We make sure Jun's sensors are understood by everyone here, that Teo has the tools, that Sofia's children know which plants to feed the soil. We keep the city honest and our neighbors safe."

    elias_hart "And us? Are we... in the plan?"
    "You let out a laugh that tastes like relief."

    asha_rivera "We are in the plan as people who show up. We'll get messy. We'll argue. We'll hold each other accountable. No grand promises, Elias. Just presence."
    "He leans his forehead to yours. There is salt on both of your skin from wind and sweat."

    elias_hart "Presence is enough for now."

    menu:
        "Close the gap and let him kiss you":
            "You close the small distance and the world narrows to warmth and the salt on his lips. It is an ending and a beginning, soft and honest; the seawall hums beneath you as if approving."
        "Stay a heartbeat apart and press your forehead to his":
            "You rest your forehead against his, savoring the quiet. No words are necessary; the contact is a vow without spectacle. The tide keeps to its rhythm and you let that be the promise."

    # --- merge ---
    "Both choices deepen your connection and confirm that you'll show up for the work and for each other."
    # [Scene: Skyward Market | Evening]
    hide asha_rivera
    hide elias_hart

    scene bg ch6_f99e88_4 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Communal percussion and a mellow saxophone; people singing in round]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Laughter, clinking bowls, the soft chatter of planning]
    "The market is a bloom of gratitude. Sofia hands out small potted cuttings tied with twine — 'to plant at home, or pass along,' she says. Teo rigs up a little stage where an old friend"
    "plays a borrowed sax; children march with tiny cardboard anchors and flags they made from old maps. The mayor stands at a table, signing the last of the permits and laughing with an elder who complains"
    "about the youth, while Jun checks over the sensors with a gentle, professional smile."
    "You move through the crowd like a seamstress, patching a conversation here, accepting a hug there, tracing the small victories as if each were a stitch in a new garment. You feel heavy with gratitude and"
    "a conviction that is steadier than the adrenaline that pushed you through the hearings — something deeper, like a current under the city."
    "Elias Hart finds you again beside a table stacked with tamales."
    show elias_hart at left:
        zoom 0.7

    elias_hart "We made them in the dead of night and still now it's perfect.' He grins. 'Not the tamales.' (He taps the wall with a knuckle toward the distance.) 'You and the neighborhood. You made it perfect."
    show asha_rivera at right:
        zoom 0.7

    asha_rivera "It's imperfect and alive. I like that better."
    "He leans in, lowers his voice."

    elias_hart "Do you want to say something... to everyone? Speech stuff? You always do that with more poetry than I ever have."
    "You: (for a moment you consider a big, oratorical thing — a speech that would go viral, framed and clipped in the city's feeds — but you choose instead to speak from the small, human center)"
    "'I'd rather we hold a workshop. Teach everyone how to tend the wall. Teach the kids about the sensors. Teach the city how to listen.'"

    elias_hart "Workshop it is. And after?' (he winks) 'Maybe later we can teach each other how to be less dramatic."

    asha_rivera "We'll get messy. We'll argue. We'll hold each other accountable. No grand promises, Elias. Just presence."
    "You smile, and it's not flippant. The mood around you is buoyant but tethered to purpose. People are already signing up for maintenance crews and mapping neighborhood rotas on a board hung between stalls."
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: The sax fades into a soft, hopeful melody; in the distance a small child shouts, 'We did it!' and someone else echoes it like an anthem.]
    "You stand beside Elias, beside Teo and Sofia, and beside the others who shoveled, sewed, argued, lobbied, and simply refused to leave. The seawall tomorrow will need tending; the permits and city approvals are paper scaffolds"
    "that will require constant communal vigilance; the storms will come again. But tonight, the barrio holds — literally and figuratively. The walls are not a final answer, but they are an anchor. They buy time and"
    "teach skill. They carry memory and possibility."
    "You let yourself feel the lightness, the rise — a collective triumph stitched from the sweat of many hands. You think of Jun calibrating sensors at dawn, of Teo elbowing his way through bureaucrats and jokes, of Sofia's laughter — and you feel a surge of clear, fierce hope."
    "Elias Hart squeezes your hand in that small, private way that says he understands the work and will show up for it. Around you, people pass platters and promise to teach, to stand watch, to pass"
    "down knowledge to their neighbors. The city shows up with paper and a willingness to be aligned. The corporations are not in the picture tonight; that fight will come again. Tonight is about the neighborhood learning"
    "to steward itself — and you, who chose this route, have helped make it possible."
    "You close your eyes for a single, deliberate breath. The market noise becomes a tide of warmth. You let gratitude move through you like the seawall moving with the waves: steady, useful, beautiful in its resilience."
    hide elias_hart
    hide asha_rivera

    scene bg ch6_f99e88_5 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Strings and chorus swell into a gentle, sustained chord]
    "You stand at the seam of what was and what will be, hand in hand with the person who helped you pull this from the city and into life. The feeling is not completion but arrival"
    "— a point on a long map where people learned an important thing: that care, organized and practiced, can be an answer."
    # [Scene: Skyward Market | Night — Closing Image]

    scene bg ch6_f99e88_6 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Single piano note resolves into silence]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Tide breathes, distant lullaby of the barrio]
    "You let the music of the market swallow the rest of the evening, and as you do, you feel the edges of exhaustion fold into a quiet, steady joy. The victory is not a banner but"
    "a practice — an anchor point the community will return to when storms come. You have kept your promise to this place, and in doing so you have remembered how to keep a promise to yourself."

    scene bg ch6_f99e88_7 at full_bg
    "THE END"
    # [GAME END]
